cc:Work.dc:title: Marbles
cc:Work.dc:description: Test of Inkscapes new on canvas gradient editing capabilities

text.tspan: I added an outline to the shape to add a little more
definition, simply duplicate the original shape, bring it to the front,
remove the fill, and set the stroke to be black.
Time for a shadow, nice and simple, just a circle filled with a
radial gradient, black to transparent, put slightly down and right
from the centre of the marble, and sent to the back.
To put a little depth back into the bottom right add
a transparent -> black radial gradient as shown.
I've used a crescent shaped path to hold it here stop any
potential effect where it wasnt wanted.
Time for a highlight. Another oval filled with
a radial gradient, make it about 2/3 width to
height then tilt it over to about 30 degrees, and
position in the top left as shown. I actually put 2
in to try and get the effect i wanted.
Time for some light, duplicate the original circle again,
fill with a radial gradient going from a light color to transparent.
What color gives the best effect will be somewhat
dependant on your base color
To give it some 3d form duplicate the circle,
then use a transparent -> semi transparent black
radial gradient as shown. (alpha on black stop is 194 here)
Create a circle of the size you want your marble/gem to be.
Fill it with a plain fill of the desired color.
(note: you can easily change this later)
This tutorial takes you through the steps requierd to make a 'marble'
like the one on the left. Its a pretty simple technique, with a
pretty nice end product.
I originally learnt this in Photoshop from
http://fyreskins.plastiqueweb.com/tutorials_gem.htm
So thanks to the guys at Fyre skins for the inspiration.
